Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Summary of yesterday's learning
*Regression analysis attempt to measure the relationship between dependent and one or more independent variables.
* Scatter plot is a collection of points on graph where each point represent value of two variables
* A population regression line indicates expected value of dependent variables conditional one or more independent variables
* Difference between actual dependent variable and given expected value is error term 
* b1= Cov(X,Y)/VAR(X).  Bo = Y° - b1X°
* Assumptions made with simple linear regression
a . Expected value of error term, conditional on independent variables,is zero.
b . All (X,Y) observation are independent and identically distributed.
c . It is unlikely that large outliers will be observed.
* OLS estimator are both unbiased and consistent
ESS:- measures the variation in dependent variable that is explained by independent variables
TSS:- measure total variation in dependent variable.
SSR :- measure the unexplained variation in dependent variable.
Coefficient of determination is measure of" goodness of fit" of regression.

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Confidence interval for regression coefficient B1
b1+- (t critical+ s)
P value is smallest level of significance for which null hypothesis can be rejected
t test with n-2 degree of freedom
t = b1- B 1/s
Predicted value of dependent variable, Y° 
Y° = Bo + b1X

Effects of heteroscedasticity
* Stardard error usually are unreliable estimate
* Coefficient estimate aren't perfect
* If standard error are too small, but coefficient estimate are not affected,t statistics are too large
Gauss Morkov says that if linear regression assumptions are true then OLS estimator are best linear combined estimator.

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Summary of today's learning
What is derivate
* Derivative is financial security with value that is derived from an underlying asset
Derivatives:- 
1- Futures
2- Option
Forward (risk associated):- 
Counterparty risk
Liquidity risk
Solution of these risks is in future
Future:- 
Underlying: what you are holding
Lot size: minimum quantity you trade
Contract size : number of shares*price
Expiry: In Equities last Thursday
Margin: need to deposit
Margins prevent risk of default
Leverage = contract value/ margin
Future is "Zero Sum Game"
Payoff in future is linear
Settlement : closing price on expiry date
Cash settlement and physical settlement
Open interest : can increase or decrease.
Volume always increase
Circuit :- if price Change by 10% coding off period begin ( trade is paused for 15 mins) another 5% change and for another 15 mins trade pauses.
Shorting: sell first and buyback if price drops
Option Greeks 
1- delta
2- gamma
3- Vega
4- theta
Delta :- rate of change in premium wrt underlying
Gamma :- rate of change of delta/ rate of change of underlying.Also called curvature of option
Theta :- far time from expiry, premium increase
Always favour seller. Premium = Time value + Intrinsic value

Summary of today's learning
Volatility :- swings
* Frequency and severity with which the market price of an investment fluctuate. More market swing means more volatility.
Implied volatility
* Represent how volatile the stock will be in near future. IV increase so making big move of underlying
Put IV is greater than call IV
On the money (faraway) : IV increase a lot
IV rank :(Today IV -low)/(high-low)*100
IV percentile : what% of days the IV was low in last 1 year.
Historical volatility: 
Looks at past events
Implied volatility:
Predict future volatility
IV tends to overstate the actual expected move nearly every stock in long term.
Options are overpriced because of volatility and if market do not fluctuate that much sellers make a lot of money.

Author: Tarun_17#4341
Content:
What is the general purpose of Options?
To Hedge Right

Let's have an intuitive understanding,
Let's assume we bought a stock expecting the price to go up
Hedgers use options to protect their assets from adverse price movements right( In our case price moving downwards ), and when the perception of risk increases, so makes the demand for this protection.
In this context, risk means volatility—the potential for more significant moves to the downside (In our case). 
The relative prices of options are driven higher by increased demand for protective options when the market anticipates greater volatility.

Content:
#data-and-analytics 
**Doubt regarding data fetching in DS_3 Goal 1.**

It says you have to fetch the data of top 100 companies according to market capitalization. 

Steps to do that: 
**step 1** Refer to tbe library i.e. nsepy which gives you the open, close, high low price,etc of any given company.  The catch is you have to pass the symbol of that company and the duration between which you want the data.


**step 2** Search for a excel file which consists the name and symbol of top 100 companies, you will get it on internet. 


**step 3** Define a function which loop through the symbol column of the excel file.


**step 4** Take one of the column of each company, for ex close price and construct the dataframe having dates in row and column as close price of 100 companies.  


**step 5** Attach last column for sensex data. And hurray your dataset is ready for next process.


If you are still stuck somewhere please let me know. 

Happy exploring 🎉

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Read more about volatility from a book : 
Volatility
1-Expected volatility
2- Implied volatility
3- historical volatility
HV : 
HV is a measure of how volatile the price movement of a security has been
during a certain period of time.
Expressed in terms of standard deviations.
IV : 
IV is a measure of how volatile the stock will be in future.
IV depends on supply and demand in market.
HV-IV Divergence
An HV-IV divergence occurs when HV declines and IV rises or vice versa.
Expected stock volatility:
Yearly standard deviations can be related to that

 of one day or one week by dividing the standard

 deviations for 1 year by sqrt of number of

 trading days that year to calculate for one day

 and multiply number of trading days sqrt to

 calculate for 1 month.

Technical analysis:
Technical analysis is the study of market data, such as past prices or volume,
which is manipulated in such a way that it better illustrates market activity.
Fundamental analysis:
Fundamental analysis is the study of economic factors that affect the
value of an asset in order to determine what it is worth.

After my First project review, I had shifted to the Index Trading Desk, where almost everyone was 15-20 Years of Experience in Market

So My desk was in between my manager and senior trader, Aftermarket closed at around 4 PM no one was there except my manager on that floor
I was noting the IVs of EOD for Nifty and Bank Nifty, Then my manager, I mean he is also a senior trader who was a pioneer in Skew Trading, came to me and reviewed my progress
Then I started to ask questions to him, He was explaining each and every minute detail with practical examples
I was wondering that the discussion went for 2.5 Hrs, Literally 2.5 Hrs a manager spending time with an Intern just to Ignite me with his knowledge was amazing 💙
Post that he discussed
- The scope of trading, 
- How a typical trading firm functions 💲
- What's the growth curve of a trader 🌠
- A day in a Life of a Trader 👨‍💻
- Strategies they are using (Typically they use only 5 Strategies with 5 different cases for each strategy): Key Learning we can take is, We don't need complex models to make money in markets, all we need is simple strategies with consistent performance and especially emotional control 
- How to be stable in every situation and emotional controlling 🙌 e.t.c

Technical learnings for the day: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1r0ONjik3MiePLZ5-OdWd1-XwAEiZfpW2kCNtzHGjCwY/edit?usp=sharing

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Summary of today's learning:- 
Option greeks
Factor that impact option price
1- Type of option
2- Underlying price
3-Time to expiration
4- Strike price
5- Volatility
6- Interest rate
7- Dividend (if paid)
Important points
* Long call and short put will benefit when underlying price rises and vice-versa
* Short call and long put will benefit when underlying price fall and vice-versa
* Increase in underlying price benefit call option buyer and decrease in same benefits holder of put option
* Moneyness= strike price- underlying price
* Strike price is below underlying price for call option it is ITM
* Higher time to expiration higher will be probability of option moving in favour of buyer
* Rise in interest rate benefits value of call and hurt put option
* Delta is probability of option expiring in the money
* Higher delta means high risk
*ITM  delta is inversely proportional to volatility.opposite for OTM
* Gamma measure change in directional risk
* Gamma will be high when strike price-stock price at T will be 0.
* Person buys option,gamma is positive
* Person sell option,gamma is negative
* Buyer of both call and put will benefit when IV go up and lose when IV go down.
* Vega is positive for long and negative for short option
* Vega is identical for both put and call
* Vega impacts only time value not intrinsic value
* Higher the time to expiration,higher would be vega or equal
* Vega highest for ATM 
* When moving towards ITM or OTM vega declines.

Author: anuj#7534
Content:
Read about cognitive ease from thinking fast and slow and here is what I learned. 

Human thinking is flawed, we have hundreds of biases in our judgments. We will believe/trust something very easily without enquiring which is easy to understand, depicted through cool visuals, or through common words which are easy to comprehend and are repeated in day to day life, said when we were  in a good mood by a person whom we like or trust. The thing is *Hitler was born in 1889* is not true just because I wrote it in italics or you were in a good mood when you read it or it was said by your crush xd.

Author: anuj#7534
Content: So what should we do?  We can't go and check everything whether it's false, we are limited by our time and energy and therefore can't invest it everywhere. I have made a rule for myself, when important things are at stake( so now the question comes what things are important? Decisions that will affect you coming months or years i.e. considerable part of your life can be considered important), I will not let these biases disbelieve the truth,just because it was said by someone who I like or I was in a good mood or is being repeated in my daily life.

Author: anuj#7534
Content: P.S. Hitler was actually born in 1889 xd, check it out on google

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Things I learnt today
Delta 
* How moneyness impact it
* How time impacts it
* How volatility impacts it
* Delta is rate of change in price of an option for every 1 point move in price of underlying.
* Delta of call option is (0-1).
* Delta of put option is (-1,0).
* New option price = Old option price + Delta*(new underlying price - old underlying price).
* Delta represent the probability of option expiring ITM.
* ITM call delta ranges from 0.5 to 1 .
* ATM call delta is 0.5 .
* OTM call delta ranges from 0 to 0.5 .
* ITM put delta ranges from -0.5 to -1 .
* ATM put delta is -0.5  .
* OTM put delta ranges from -1 to -0.5 .
* Delta of underlying is 1.
* Option having higher delta are more responsive to change in price of underlying.
* For ITM ,delta of an option closer to expiry is higher and vice-versa.
* For OTM ,delta of an option closer to expiry is lower and vice-versa.
* For ATM ,delta of an option closer to expiry is lower and vice-versa.
* For ITM ,delta of an option higher if low volatility and vice-versa.
* For OTM ,delta of an option higher means high volatility.
* Value of delta keeps changing as other variables do 
* Important : call delta + put delta = 1.

Author: mewtwo#5793
Content:
Hello everyone, I have completed my Goal 4 in Data science. It was very challenging for me as well as very informative and knowledgeable...

Here are my learnings...

1. I learned about decision trees and how to make predictions using these trees, I found it very useful if you know how to ask optimal questions to classify things.
2. I also learned about ensembling methods.. and It shows how from many small decision trees or models we can create our own ensembled model with better predictions. It is the thing that takes most of my time in the goal but at the same time returns the most too.
3. Then I learned different types of ensembling models made on decision trees like AdaBoost, LightGBM, XGBoost, CatBoost, and GradientBoost. 

After learning this stuff when I faced the real-world scenario given in the problem statement, first I was not able to get how I will use these things in the problem... eventually reading notebooks and getting the idea make things more clear to me and finally I did what is needed in the problem. Overall it was a nice experience for me to work on this problem and I learned much from this.

Thanks to @utkarsh for helping me out in many places..

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Summary of today's learning
Gamma
* How it impacts delta, how moneyness impact it.
* How time to expiration and volatility impacts it.
* Gamma is rate of change of delta for every 1 point move in price of underlying.
* Delta measures directional risk and gamma measure change in directional risk.
* Rising gamma mean any change in price of underlying would be greater change in delta, which leads to greater change in option price.
* At ATM gamma is highest. When move towards ITM or OTM gamma reduces.
* Deep ITM or OTM gamma is 0.
* Gamma for buyer is positive while for seller is negative.
* Gamma causes delta of long option to move 0 when call option underlying price decrease or rises for put
* Seller wants underlying to be stable.  *Gamma variation with time to expiration
                  
ITM.                        Short time.          Higher
                                Long time.          Lower
ATM to OTM.        Short time.           Higher
                                Long time.         Lower
ATM.                       Short time           Increase
                               Long time.         Decrease

* Gamma of ITM or OTM reduce when time to expiration is near.
* Deep ITM or OTM gamma falls for short time to expire and vice-versa.
* Gamma of ATM increase as time in expiration near.
* Gamma high for ATM with low volatility and it starts reducing as volatility increase.
* As volatility increase, gamma of ITM and OTM reduce.
* When deep OTM or ITM , increase in volatility cause gamma to be higher.
* Gamma curve tends to be sensitive to price change in low volatility than to price change in high volatility.
* Signs of delta and gamma 
                            Delta.                    Gamma
Long call.          Positive.               Positive
Short call.          Negative.             Negative
Long put.           Negative.            Positive
Short put.           Positive.              Negative

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Summary of what I learnt today
Theta
* Theta measure impact of time on price of option.
* Theta is defined as change in option price for a one unit change in time left to expiration.
* Theta is defined as lost of option value as a result of time decay.
* Time decay is the rate at which the value of an option erodes with each passing day.
* Theta works in favour of option writer and against option buyer
* Theta is negative for long position and positive for short position.
* Price of an option reduces each day by theta.
* Call value erode slightly Higher than put.
* ATM 
* has highest theta
* Theta increase in absolute value with passing days , before starting to rise exponentially as expiration gets closer.
* ATM is risky because of rapid declining theta will rapidly erode time value of option.
* ITM
* Intrinsic value form larger component
* Have low theta , deep ITM have low loss in terms of time value.
* Theta tends to increase at slower rate, before starting to fall sharply as expiry gets closer 
* OTM 
* Have only time value no intrinsic value
* Deep OTM , lower time value lower theta
* Theta increase at slower rate before exponential decrease
* Higher volatility, higher time value of an option , higher option value.
* Fall in time value of option with high volatility tends to be greater than fall in time value option with low volatility.
* Low volatility, fall in time value is steadier.

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Revised volatility and read about vega
* Volatility is rate at which price of an asset fluctuate over time.
* Historical volatility measures the dispersion around mean for daily returns on an Annualised basis.
* Implied volatility is measure of future volatility.
* Vega is defined as change in option price for every 1% change in implied volatility.
* Higher the IV higher would be change in option price.
* Buyer of a call or put benefit when IV go up.
* Seller of a call or put benefit when IV go down.
* Vega is positive for long position and negative for short position.
* Long means you have long vega exposure and short means you have short vega exposure.
* Rising volatility works against option seller.
* Vega is identical for all call and put.
* Vega impacts only time value component of option price that is extrinsic value not the Intrinsic value.
* Higher time to expiration, higher would be vega
* Vega is highest for ATM.
* As moving either ITM or OTM vega starts declining
* Vega is too low for deep ITM and OTM.
* Maximum impact of change in IV tends to occur for options that are ATM because they tend to have highest vega.
* Closer the probability of option expiring ITM moves towards extreme lower will be vega

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Summary of today's learning
Black scholes model
* It is differential equation widely used to price option contract.
* It requires 5 input variables, strike price of an option, current stock price, Time to expiration, risk free rate and volatility.
* Due to certain assumptions price deviate from real world results.
* Only used in European option as it doesn't take into account that American option can be exercised before time to expiration.
* BSM posits that instrument, such as stock shares or future contact, will have lognormal distribution of prices following a random walk with constant drift and Volatility.
* It is theoretically possible for option seller to set rational prices for the option that they are selling.
* Model predicts that the price of heavily traded asset follow a geometric browninan motion with constant Volatility and drift.
Assumptions :- 
* No dividend are paid out during the life of an option.
* Markets are random
* There are no transactions costs in buying an option.
* Risk free rate and volatility of the underlying asset are known and constant
* Returns on the underlying asset are log- normally distributed
* Option is European and can be only exercise at expiration.
Volatility skew :- 
* BSM assume stock price follow lognormal distribution because asset prices cannot be negative.
* Asset prices are observed to have significant right skewness and some degree of kutosis. This means high risk Downward moves often happens in market than normal distribution.
Drawback :-
* Used for only European call and do not consider American option can be exercised before expiration.
* Assume dividend and risk free rate are constant, but this may not be true in reality.
* Model also assume volatility remain constant over option life.

Have you heard of **DALL-E 2** ?
Its a new creation from AI research group ***OpenAI(co-founded by Elon Musk)***
**A text to image generation program** that can create realistic images and art from a description in natural language.
> DALL·E 2 can create original, realistic images and art from a
> text description. It can combine concepts, attributes, and styles.

> It can make realistic edits to existing images from a natural language caption. It can add and remove elements while taking shadows, reflections, and textures into account.

> It can take an image and create different
> variations of it inspired by the original.

`It has learned the relationship between images and the text used to describe them. It uses a process called “diffusion,” which starts with a pattern of random dots and gradually alters that pattern towards an image when it recognizes specific aspects of that image.`

> The dog image was generated from the description “A Shiba Inu dog wearing a beret and black turtleneck”

Seems interesting ?

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Summary of today's learning
Mutual fund
* Type of investment consisting of portfolios of stocks, bonds or other securities.
* It give small or individual investors access to diversified, professionally managed portfolios at low price.
* Mutual fund are divided into several categories representing kind of securities they invest in, their investment objective and type of return they seek.
* Mutual funds charge annual fees or commission in some cases, which affect their overall return.
* Overwhelming majority of money in employer sponsored retirement plan goes into mutual funds.
* Value of mutual fund company depends on performance of security it decides to buy.
* Unlike stock, mutual fund shares do not give its holders any voting rights.
* Voting rights :- right of a shareholder to vote on matters of corporate policy, issuing new securities.
* Net Asset value :- represent the net value of an equity and is calculated as total value of entity's assets minus total value of liabilities.
* How investors earns return
* From dividend
* If fund sells securities that have increased in price, capital gain.
* If fund holding increase in price but are not sold by fund manager, fund's share increase in price.

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Revision notes
Delta :- 
* Delta is rate of change in price of an option for every 1 point move in price of underlying.
* Call option : (0,1) Put option : (-1,0)
* Delta represent the probability of an option expiring in ITM
* Call ITM : 0.5-1    ATM : 0.5      OTM : 0 to 0.5
* Put ITM : (-0.5,-1).  ATM : -0.5.   OTM : 0 to -0.5
* Delta of underlying is 1
* For OTM , delta of option close to expiry are lower 
*  For ITM , delta of option close to expiry are higher
* For ATM , delta of option close to expiry are lower
* For OTM and ITM delta lower if underlying has  low and high volatility respectively.
* Call delta + put delta = 1
* Delta measures directional risk
* Gamma 
* Gamma is rate of change of delta for every 1 point move in underlying price
* Gamma is highest for ATM
* When move towards ITM or OTM gamma reduces
* Deep ITM or deep OTM gamma is 0.
* Buyer : gamma (+ve), seller : gamma (-ve)
* ITM , short time to expiration, gamma higher than long time
* ATM - OTM , short time , gamma higher than long time
* ATM , short time , gamma higher than long time
* Gamma is high for ATM with low volatility and it starts reducing as volatility increase
* With increasing volatility gamma of ITM and OTM reduce
* For ITM or OTM, as time to expiration reduce gamma reduces
* Theta
* Change in option price for a one unit change in time left to expiration
* Theta works in favour of option seller and against buyers
* Negative for long call and long put
* Call value erode slightly Higher rate than put.
* ATM has highest theta
* ITM, intrinsic value form larger component of option price
* OTM have only time value
* Higher the volatility, higher will be theta

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
* Vega
* Change in option price for a one percent change in IV
* Vega is positive for long position
* Long means having long vega exposure
* Vega is identical for call and put
* Vega impacts only time value component of option price
* Higher time to expiration, higher would be vega
* Vega highest for ATM
* Maximum impact of change in IV tends to occur for options that are ATM because they tend to have highest vega

Author: utkarsh#1616
Content:
Hey @everyone 
Back with another AI Creation.
How would you feel if you just pass question to the machine and it will **code for you**?
**So what does this mean for programming? Does it mean that there is no point in learning programming because it will get fully automated?**

We don't believe so. Here is what we think the impact will be:

> We'll have tools that help us code faster. We'll see more sophisticated code generation and refactor tools, and repetitive coding tasks -- the moments you see yourself copy-pasting code -- might get automated away wholly.
> 
> AI will make it easier to learn programming (and many other things). Imagine Codecademy-like courses entirely guided by AI with conversational abilities.
> 
> Eventually, AI will influence how we design programming languages, and a new class of languages will emerge. Since computers will be better and faster than humans at generating code, the act of programming itself might change. Who knows, we might be able to program by talking or even by moving in VR/AR.

At some point -- probably not in the near future -- `the word "coding" will disappear `from our lexicon because programming will stop requiring code and instead be about the pure act of solving problems using computers making it accessible to more and more people.

In the meantime, if you haven't yet, you should still learn how to code and get good at it. It's unlikely that things will change meaningfully in the short-term, and coding is still the best way to program computers. But keep your eyes open to the future, as many AI groups like Repl.it is building the most advanced programming environment regardless of the modality.

Read more about how can you code simply using AI or understand using AI https://blog.replit.com/codingai

Author: Priyanshi#7806
Content:
Summing up today's learning
Types of mutual funds
* Equity fund :- this sort of fund invests principally in stocks. Within this group are various subcategories.
* Fixed income fund :- focuses on investments that pay a set rate of return, such as government bonds, corporate bonds, or other debt instruments
* Index fund :- investment strategy is based on the belief that it is very hard, and often expensive, to try to beat the market consistently.
* Balanced fund :- Balanced funds invest in a hybrid of asset classes, whether stocks, bonds, money market instruments, or alternative investments. The objective is to reduce the risk of exposure across asset classes.
* Money market fund :- consists of safe , short-term debt instruments, mostly government treasury bills.
* Income funds :- These funds invest primarily in government and high-quality corporate debt, holding these bonds until maturity in order to provide interest streams.
* International funds :- invests only in assets located outside your home country.
* Speciality fund :- consists of funds that have proved to be popular but don't necessarily belong to the more rigid categories.
* Regional fund :- make it easier to focus on a specific geographic area of the world.
* Socially responsible fund :- invest only in companies that meet the criteria of certain guidelines or beliefs.
* Exchange traded fund :- they are structured as investment trusts that are traded on stock exchanges and have the added benefits of the features of stocks.

Author: Divyansh#4279
Content:
Not feeling good as was unable to make up for a commitment made. After self-assessment realised that this bad feeling was not because the commitment was not completed but because I was unable to provide even a single second. If I had given it some time, I know it would have resulted in something fruitful. And this thought of zero effort is what has disappointed me. 

Realisation-: Efforts should be made as it results in growth (high or low) and that growth serves as a fuel (hope of improving) for the coming day. 
However, no efforts = no growth = self-defeating thoughts = weak and detained mind = no effort and you get stuck in this loop.

Also, will make sure tomorrow doesn't result in self-disappointment. 

Another thought -: Self-assessment or self-awareness is something that should be used as a very precious tool as it has the power to convert your bad & disappointing thoughts into good & motivating ones. Just by assessing the situation, everything gets organised and so do your thoughts, they reach the place they should always be - "THE SHELVES OF POSITIVITY"

Content:
We could calculate the Black Scholes Option Price using Python (or simply using a calculator), but the reality is that the BS formula does not determine option prices (lol).

Those with experience with the stock & options market would understand, that the demand and supply of an asset determine its value/price. So why bother with the formula and why it’s worth the Nobel prize?

Author: Keshav Bidawatka#6333
Content:
https://www.myhatchpad.com/insight/how-to-excel-as-a-product-manager-at-an-early-stage-startup/

Found this blog very interesting. I strongly suggest those interested in being PMs at early-stage startups to give it 2 minutes. @anuj @Mohit @sourabkumar004 @Khush @vedant11 @argus @Aman Vishwakarma 

Two learnings stood out for me:
1. The thing that product people often fail to appreciate is how hard it is to go from an idea to having even a couple hundred thousand dollars of revenue. It’s a skillset that product people rarely have themselves.
That empathy ultimately enables you to have conversations with the founders around pivoting and adapting existing product strategies to help prepare for the next stage of growth and make the company successful. But that level of respect and understanding must always be brought with you; otherwise, you’re just going to set yourself up to fail.

2. **An often-overlooked aspect of early-stage product management is that different PMs come in and add value at certain stages:**

**You want to have the openness to serve for as long as you’re useful and recognize that there’s nothing wrong with moving on to the next thing and passing the baton to someone else to take the company to the next level.**
